# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1944-new-york-cubans-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] The **1944 Boston Braves season** was the 74th season of the franchise, 69th as a charter member of the National League.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] The Braves finished in sixth place with a 65–89 (.422) record, 40 games from the pennant-winning St.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] They attracted 208,691 fans to Braves Field during this wartime season, eighth and last in the NL and 16th of the 16 teams then classified as major league.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] On January 21, 1944, the Braves were acquired by "The Three Little Steam Shovels" — all Boston-area heavy construction magnates; Louis R.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] Perini, 40, became the principal owner, with C.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] Joseph Maney, 59, and Guido Rugo, 45, as minority investors.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] The three were investors in the previous ownership group, headed by club president J.A.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] Robert Quinn, 73, who remained with the team as chief executive, general manager, and a member of its board of directors.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] On August 10, 1944, pitcher Red Barrett pitched a complete-game 2-hit shutout against the Cincinnati Reds at Crosley Field, winning 2–0, requiring only 58 pitches and lasting only 1 hour 15 minutes.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-braves-season] It was the fewest number of pitches thrown in a 9-inning complete game and was the quickest night game in MLB history.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-red-sox-season] The **1944 Boston Red Sox season** was the 44th season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished fourth in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 77 losses, 12 games behind the St.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The **1944 Brooklyn Dodgers** saw a constant roster turnover as players left for service in World War II.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The team finished the season in seventh place in the National League.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-chicago-cubs-season] The **1944 Chicago Cubs season** was the 73rd season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 69th in the National League and the 29th at Wrigley Field.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished fourth in the National League with a record of 75–79.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1944 Chicago White Sox season** was the White Sox's 44th season in the major leagues, and their 45th season overall.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-chicago-white-sox-season] They finished with a record of 71–83, good enough for seventh place in the American League, 18 games behind the first place St.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1944 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] It consisted of the Cincinnati Reds attempting to win the National League, although finishing in third place.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] They finished the season with 89 wins and 65 losses.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] On June 10, Joe Nuxhall made his major league debut.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] At age 15, he is (as of the 2022 season) the youngest confirmed player ever to play Major League Baseball.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] He pitched just two-thirds of an inning, giving up 5 runs on 2 hits and 5 walks.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cincinnati-reds-season] He would not appear in the majors again until 1952.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cleveland-indians-season] The **1944 Cleveland Indians season** was a season in American major league baseball.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-cleveland-indians-season] The team finished fifth in the American League with a record of 72–82–1.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-new-york-cubans-season] The **1944 New York Cubans** were a baseball team that competed in Negro National League (NNL) during the 1944 baseball season.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-new-york-cubans-season] The team compiled a 53–29–2 record (29–21–2 against NNL opponents) and finished in third place in the NNL.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-new-york-cubans-season] José María Fernández was the team's manager.
[src:1944-new-york-cubans-season/1944-new-york-cubans-season] Other regular players included left fielder Rogelio Linares, shortstop Rabbit Martínez, center fielder José Vargas, second baseman Javier Pérez, catcher Lou Louden, first baseman Dave Thomas, pitcher Pat Scantlebury, Luis Tiant Sr., Victor Greenidge, and Dave Barnhill.
